# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloud-entitlements-ciem
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In physical security and information security, **access control** (**AC**) is the action of deciding whether a subject should be granted or denied access to an object (for example, a place or a resource).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The act of *accessing* may mean consuming, entering, or using.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] It is often used interchangeably with authorization, although the authorization may be granted well in advance of the access control decision.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Access control on digital platforms is also termed admission control.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The protection of external databases is essential to preserve digital security.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Access control is considered to be a significant aspect of privacy that should be further studied.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] **Access control policy** (also **access policy**) is part of an organization’s security policy.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In order to verify the access control policy, organizations use an access control model.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] General security policies require designing or selecting appropriate security controls to satisfy an organization's risk appetite - access policies similarly require the organization to design or select access controls.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Broken access control is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Geographical access control may be enforced by personnel (e.g. border guard, bouncer, ticket checker), or with a device such as a turnstile.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] There may be fences to avoid circumventing this access control.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] An alternative of access control in the strict sense (physically controlling access itself) is a system of checking authorized presence, see e.g.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] A variant is exit control, e.g. of a shop (checkout) or a country.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The term access control refers to the practice of restricting entrance to a property, a building, or a room to authorized persons.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Physical access control can be achieved by a human (a guard, bouncer, or receptionist), through mechanical means such as locks and keys, or through technological means such as access control systems like the mantrap.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Within these environments, physical key management may also be employed as a means of further managing and monitoring access to mechanically keyed areas or access to certain small assets.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Physical access control is a matter of who, where, and when.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] An access control system determines who is allowed to enter or exit, where they are allowed to exit or enter, and when they are allowed to enter or exit.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Historically, this was partially accomplished through keys and locks.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] When a door is locked, only someone with a key can enter through the door, depending on how the lock is configured.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not allow restriction of the key holder to specific times or dates.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not provide records of the key used on any specific door, and the keys can be easily copied or transferred to an unauthorized person.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] When a mechanical key is lost or the key holder is no longer authorized to use the protected area, the locks must be re-keyed.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Electronic access control (EAC) uses computers to solve the limitations of mechanical locks and keys.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] It is particularly difficult to guarantee identification (a critical component of authentication) with mechanical locks and keys.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] A wide range of credentials can be used to replace mechanical keys, allowing for complete authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The electronic access control system grants access based on the credential presented.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] When access is granted, the resource is unlocked for a predetermined time and the transaction is recorded.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] When access is refused, the resource remains locked and the attempted access is recorded.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The system will also monitor the resource and alarm if the resource is forcefully unlocked or held open too long after being unlocked.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] When a credential is presented to a reader, the reader sends the credential's information, usually a number, to a control panel, a highly reliable processor.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The control panel compares the credential's number to an access control list, grants or denies the presented request, and sends a transaction log to a database.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] When access is denied based on the access control list, the door remains locked.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] If there is a match between the credential and the access control list, the control panel operates a relay that in turn unlocks the resource.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The control panel also ignores an opening signal to prevent an alarm.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Often the reader provides feedback, such as a flashing red LED for an access denied and a flashing green LED for an access granted.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The above description illustrates a single factor transaction.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Credentials can be passed around, thus subverting the access control list.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] For example, Alice has access rights to the server room, but Bob does not.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Alice either gives Bob her credential, or Bob takes it; he now has access to the server room.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] To prevent this, two-factor authentication can be used.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In a two factor transaction, the presented credential and a second factor are needed for access to be granted; another factor can be a PIN code, a second credential, operator intervention, or a biometric input.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Passwords are a common means of verifying a user's identity before access is given to information systems.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In addition, a fourth factor of authentication is now recognized: someone you know, whereby another person who knows you can provide a human element of authentication in situations where systems have been set up to allow for such scenarios.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] For example, a user may have their password, but have forgotten their smart card.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In such a scenario, if the user is known to designated cohorts, the cohorts may provide their smart card and password, in combination with the extant factor of the user in question, and thus provide two factors for the user with the missing credential, giving three factors overall to allow access.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] A credential is a physical/tangible object, a piece of knowledge, or a facet of a person's physical being that enables an individual access to a given physical facility or computer-based information system.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Typically, credentials can be something a person knows (such as a number or PIN code), something they have (such as an access badge), something they are (such as a biometric feature), something they do (measurable behavioural patterns), or some combination of these items.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] This is known as multi-factor authentication.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The typical credential is an access card or key-fob, and newer software can also turn users' smartphones into access devices.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] There are many card technologies including magnetic stripe, bar code, Wiegand, 125 kHz proximity, 26-bit card-swipe, contact smart cards, and contactless smart cards.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Also available are key-fobs, which are more compact than ID cards, and attach to a key ring.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Biometric technologies include fingerprint, facial recognition, iris recognition, retinal scan, voice, and hand geometry.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The built-in biometric technologies found on newer smartphones can also be used as credentials in conjunction with access software running on mobile devices.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In addition to older more traditional card access technologies, newer technologies such as near-field communication (NFC), Bluetooth low energy or Ultra-wideband (UWB) can also communicate user credentials to readers for system or building access.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Access control decisions are made by comparing the credentials to an access control list.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] This look-up can be done by a host or server, by an access control panel, or by a reader.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The development of access control systems has observed a steady push of the look-up out from a central host to the edge of the system, or the reader.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The predominant topology circa 2009 is hub and spoke with a control panel as the hub, and the readers as the spokes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The look-up and control functions are by the control panel.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The spokes communicate through a serial connection; usually RS-485.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Some manufactures are pushing the decision making to the edge by placing a controller at the door.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Some readers may have additional features such as a display and function buttons for data collection purposes (i.e. clock-in/clock-out events for attendance reports), camera/speaker/microphone for intercom, or smart card read/write support.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] All the RS-485-related advantages and disadvantages also apply.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The advantages and disadvantages of IP controllers apply to the IP readers as well.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The most common security risk of intrusion through an access control system is by simply following a legitimate user through a door, referred to as "tailgating".
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Often, a legitimate user may hold the door for the intruder as an act of common courtesy.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] This risk can be minimized through security awareness training of the user population, or more active means such as turnstiles which admit only one person at a time.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In very high-security applications, this risk is minimized by using a sally port (sometimes called a "security vestibule" or "mantrap"), where operator intervention is required, presumably after confirming valid identification.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The second most common risk is from levering a door open by sheer brute force.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] This is relatively difficult on properly-secured doors with ruggedized strikes or high holding force magnetic locks.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Fully-implemented access control systems include forced-door monitoring alarms.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] These vary in effectiveness, often failing from high false-positive alarms, poor database configuration, or lack of active intrusion monitoring.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Most newer access control systems incorporate some type of "door prop" alarm to inform system administrators of a door left open longer than a specified length of time.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The third most common security risk arises from natural disasters.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In order to mitigate this risk, the structure of the building, down to the quality of the network and computer equipment is crucial.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] From an organizational perspective, the leadership will need to adopt and implement an All Hazards Plan, or Incident Response Plan.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The highlights of any incident plan recommended by the National Incident Management System usually include pre-incident planning, during-incident actions, disaster recovery, and after-action review.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] An attack similar to levering is breaking through cheap partition walls, typically made of wallboard or cinder blocks.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In shared tenant spaces, the divisional wall is a vulnerability.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] A vulnerability along the same lines is the breaking of sidelight windows located next to doors.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Spoofing of locking hardware is fairly simple and more elegant than levering.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] A strong magnet can operate the solenoid controlling bolts in electric locking hardware.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Motorized locks, more prevalent in Europe than in the US, are also susceptible to this attack using a doughnut-shaped magnet.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] It is also possible to manipulate the power to the lock either by removing or adding current, although most Access Control systems incorporate battery back-up systems, and the locks are almost always located on the secure side of the door.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Access cards themselves have proven vulnerable to sophisticated attacks.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Enterprising hackers have built portable readers that capture the card number from a user's proximity card.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The hacker simply walks by the user, reads the card, and later presents the number to a reader securing the door.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] This is possible when card numbers are sent in the clear, no encryption being used.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] To counter this, dual authentication methods, such as a card plus a PIN should always be used.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Many access control credentials use unique serial numbers which are programmed in sequential order during manufacturing.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In a method known as a "sequential attack", if an intruder has a credential once used in the system, they can simply increment or decrement the serial number until they find a credential that is currently authorized in the system.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Specifying credentials with random unique serial numbers is recommended to counter this threat.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In addition, increasingly long lockout timeout intervals after a credential failure will make automated repeated attacks infeasible.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Finally, most electric locking hardware still uses mechanical keys as a fail-over.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Most conventional mechanical key locks are vulnerable to bumping.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In computer security, general access control includes authentication, authorization, and audit.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] A more narrow definition of access control would cover only access approval, whereby the system makes a decision to grant or reject an access request from an already authenticated subject, based on what the subject is authorized to access.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Authentication and access control are often combined into a single operation, so that access is approved based on successful authentication, or based on an anonymous access token.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Authentication methods and tokens include passwords, biometric analysis, physical keys, electronic keys and devices, hidden paths, social barriers, and monitoring by humans and automated systems.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In any access-control model, the entities that can perform actions on the system are called *subjects*, and the entities representing resources to which access may need to be controlled are called *objects* (see also Access Control Matrix).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Subjects and objects should both be considered as software entities, rather than as human users: any human users can only have an effect on the system via the software entities that they control.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In some models, for example the object-capability model, any software entity can potentially act as both subject and object.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] As of 2014, access-control models tend to fall into one of two classes: those based on capabilities and those based on access control lists (ACLs).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Both capability-based and ACL-based models have mechanisms to allow access rights to be granted to all members of a *group* of subjects (often the group is itself modeled as a subject).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Access to accounts can be enforced through many types of controls.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Discretionary Access Control (DAC) In DAC, the data owner determines who can access specific resources.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] For example, a system administrator may create a hierarchy of files to be accessed based on certain permissions.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Graph-based Access Control (GBAC) Compared to other approaches like RBAC or ABAC, the main difference is that in GBAC access rights are defined using an organizational query language instead of total enumeration.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] History-Based Access Control (HBAC) Access is granted or declined based on the real-time evaluation of a history of activities of the inquiring party, e.g. behavior, time between requests, content of requests.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] For example, the access to a certain service or data source can be granted or declined on the personal behavior, e.g. the request interval exceeds one query per second.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] History-of-Presence Based Access Control (HPBAC) Access control to resources is defined in terms of presence policies that need to be satisfied by presence records stored by the requestor.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Policies are usually written in terms of frequency, spread and regularity.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Identity-Based Access Control (IBAC) Using this network administrators can more effectively manage activity and access based on individual needs.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Lattice-Based Access Control (LBAC) A lattice is used to define the levels of security that an object may have and that a subject may have access to.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The subject is only allowed to access an object if the security level of the subject is greater than or equal to that of the object.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Mandatory Access Control (MAC) In MAC, users do not have much freedom to determine who has access to their files.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] For example, security clearance of users and classification of data (as confidential, secret or top secret) are used as security labels to define the level of trust.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Organization-Based Access Control (OrBAC) OrBAC model allows the policy designer to define a security policy independently of the implementation.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Relationship-Based Access Control (ReBAC) A subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) RBAC allows access based on the job title.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] RBAC largely eliminates discretion when providing access to objects.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] For example, a human resources specialist should not have permissions to create network accounts; this should be a role reserved for network administrators.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Rule-Based Access Control (RAC) RAC method, also referred to as Rule-Based Role-Based Access Control (RB-RBAC), is largely context based.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Example of this would be allowing students to use labs only during a certain time of day; it is the combination of students' RBAC-based information system access control with the time-based lab access rules.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Responsibility Based Access Control Information is accessed based on the responsibilities assigned to an actor or a business role.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Subscription-Based Access Control (SBAC) SBAC assigns permissions based on a user's subscription status, automating the process of granting, modifying, or revoking access as users subscribe, upgrade, downgrade, or cancel.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] SBAC is particularly relevant for SaaS business, where access to features, data, or services is tied to a user's active plan.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Unlike RBAC or ABAC, which define permissions based on roles or attributes, SBAC dynamically distributes roles and policies based on billing status, ensuring real-time access alignment.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Several regulatory frameworks impose specific access control requirements on organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement technical access controls for electronic protected health information (ePHI), including unique user identification, emergency access procedures, automatic logoff, and encryption and decryption mechanisms.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The proposed HIPAA Security Rule update (NPRM, December 2024) would strengthen these requirements by mandating multi-factor authentication for all access to ePHI.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 7 mandates that access to cardholder data be restricted on a need-to-know basis, while Requirement 8 requires unique identification for each person with computer access.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) addresses access control extensively in Special Publication 800-53 through the AC (Access Control) control family, which includes policies for account management, separation of duties, least privilege, and session controls.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] A technique used to define or restrict the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data onto, a storage device.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The definition or restriction of the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data into, a storage device.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] The process of limiting access to the resources of an AIS (Automated Information System) to authorized users, programs, processes, or other systems.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] That function performed by the resource controller that allocates system resources to satisfy user requests.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] This definition depends on several other technical terms from Federal Standard 1037C.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] Special public member methods – **accessors** (aka **getters**) and **mutator methods** (often called **setters**) are used to control changes to class variables in order to prevent unauthorized access and data corruption.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/access-control] In public policy, access control to restrict access to systems ("authorization") or to track or monitor behavior within systems ("accountability") is an implementation feature of using trusted systems for security or social control.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC is a method of implementing access control policies that is highly adaptable and can be customized using a wide range of attributes, making it suitable for use in distributed or rapidly changing environments.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] The only limitations on the policies that can be implemented with ABAC are the capabilities of the computational language and the availability of relevant attributes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC policy rules are generated as Boolean functions of the subject's attributes, the object's attributes, and the environment attributes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Unlike role-based access control (RBAC), which defines roles that carry a specific set of privileges associated with them and to which subjects are assigned, ABAC can express complex rule sets that can evaluate many different attributes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Through defining consistent subject and object attributes into security policies, ABAC eliminates the need for explicit authorizations to individuals’ subjects needed in a non-ABAC access method, reducing the complexity of managing access lists and groups.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute values can be set-valued or atomic-valued.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Set-valued attributes contain more than one atomic value.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Atomic-valued attributes contain only one atomic value.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Examples are *clearance* and *sensitivity*.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be compared to static values or to one another, thus enabling relation-based access control.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control is sometimes referred to as **policy-based access control** (**PBAC**) or **claims-based access control** (**CBAC**), which is a Microsoft-specific term.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] The key standards that implement ABAC are XACML and ALFA (XACML).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] The PDP or Policy Decision Point is the brain of the architecture.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] This is the piece which evaluates incoming requests against policies it has been configured with.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] The PIP or Policy Information Point bridges the PDP to external sources of attributes e.g.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be about anything and anyone.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Policies are statements that bring together attributes to express what can happen and is not allowed.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Policies in ABAC can be granting or denying policies.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Policies can also be local or global and can be written in a way that they override other policies.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] With ABAC you can have an unlimited number of policies that cater to many different scenarios and technologies.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Historically, access control models have included mandatory access control (MAC), discretionary access control (DAC), and more recently role-based access control (RBAC).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] These access control models are user-centric and do not take into account additional parameters such as resource information, the relationship between the user (the requesting entity) and the resource, and dynamic information, e.g. time of the day or user IP.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC tries to address this by defining access control based on attributes which describe the requesting entity (the user), the targeted object or resource, the desired action (view, edit, delete), and environmental or contextual information.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] This is why access control is said to be attribute-based.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] XACML, the eXtensible Access Control Markup Language, defines an architecture (shared with ALFA and NGAC), a policy language, and a request/response scheme.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] It does not handle attribute management (user attribute assignment, object attribute assignment, environment attribute assignment) which is left to traditional IAM tools, databases, and directories.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Companies, including every branch in the United States military, have started using ABAC.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] At a basic level, ABAC protects data with 'IF/THEN/AND' rules rather than assign data to users.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] The US Department of Commerce has made this a mandatory practice and the adoption is spreading throughout several governmental and military agencies.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] The concept of ABAC can be applied at any level of the technology stack and an enterprise infrastructure.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] For example, ABAC can be used at the firewall, server, application, database, and data layer.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] The use of attributes bring additional context to evaluate the legitimacy of any request for access and inform the decision to grant or deny access.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] An important consideration when evaluating ABAC solutions is to understand its potential overhead on performance and its impact on the user experience.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] It is expected that the more granular the controls, the higher the overhead.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC can be used to apply attribute-based, fine-grained authorization to the API methods or functions.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] For instance, a banking API may expose an `approveTransaction(transId)` method.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] The API receives the call and authenticates the user.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] The PDP retrieves the ABAC policy and necessary attributes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] If the decision is Permit, the underlying API business logic is called.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Otherwise the API returns an error or access denied.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] One of the key benefits to ABAC is that the authorization policies and attributes can be defined in a technology neutral way.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] This means policies defined for APIs or databases can be reused in the application space.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] The same process and flow as the one described in the API section applies here too.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Security for databases has long been specific to the database vendors: Oracle VPD, IBM FGAC, and Microsoft RLS are all means to achieve fine-grained ABAC-like security.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Data security typically goes one step further than database security and applies control directly to the data element.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] This is often referred to as data-centric security.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] On traditional relational databases, ABAC policies can control access to data at the table, column, field, cell and sub-cell using logical controls with filtering conditions and masking based on attributes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be data, user, session or tools based to deliver the greatest level of flexibility in dynamically granting/denying access to a specific data element.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] On big data, and distributed file systems such as Hadoop, ABAC applied at the data layer control access to folder, sub-folder, file, sub-file and other granular.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control can also be applied to Big Data systems like Hadoop.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] Policies similar to those used previously can be applied when retrieving data from data lakes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] As of Windows Server 2012, Microsoft has implemented an ABAC approach to controlling access to files and folders.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] This is achieved through dynamic access control (DAC) and Security Descriptor Definition Language (SDDL).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/attribute-based-access-control] SDDL can be seen as an ABAC language as it uses metadata of the user (claims) and of the file/ folder to control access.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/identity-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle means giving any user accounts or processes only those privileges which are essentially vital to perform its intended functions.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, a user account for the sole purpose of creating backups does not need to install software: hence, it has rights only to run backup and backup-related applications.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] Any other privileges, such as installing new software, are blocked.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle applies also to a personal computer user who usually does work in a normal user account, and opens a privileged, password protected account only when the situation absolutely demands it.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] When applied to users, the terms *least user access* or *least-privileged user account* (LUA) are also used, referring to the concept that all user accounts should run with as few privileges as possible, and also launch applications with as few privileges as possible.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle (of least privilege) is widely recognized as an important design consideration towards enhancing and giving a much needed 'Boost' to the protection of data and functionality from faults (fault tolerance) and malicious behavior.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, there exist multiple competing definitions of true (least privilege).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] As program complexity increases rapidly, so do the number of potential issues, rendering a predictive approach impractical.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] Examples include the values of variables it may process, addresses it will need, or the precise time such things will be required.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] Object capability systems allow, for instance, deferring granting a single-use privilege until the time when it will be used.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] Currently, the closest practical approach is to eliminate privileges that can be manually evaluated as unnecessary.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] The resulting set of privileges typically exceeds the true minimum required privileges for the process.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] Another limitation is the granularity of control that the operating environment has over privileges for an individual process.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, it is rarely possible to control a process's access to memory, processing time, I/O device addresses or modes with the precision needed to facilitate only the precise set of privileges a process will require.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] Denning, in his paper "Fault Tolerant Operating Systems", set it in a broader perspective among "The four fundamental principles of fault tolerance".
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] "Dynamic assignments of privileges" was earlier discussed by Roger Needham in 1972.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] Historically, the oldest instance of (least privilege) is probably the source code of *login.c*, which begins execution with super-user permissions and—the instant they are no longer necessary—dismisses them via *setuid()* with a non-zero argument as demonstrated in the Version 6 Unix source code.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] The kernel always runs with maximum privileges since it is the operating system core and has hardware access.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] One of the principal responsibilities of an operating system, particularly a multi-user operating system, is management of the hardware's availability and requests to access it from running processes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] When the kernel crashes, the mechanisms by which it maintains state also fail.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] Therefore, even if there is a way for the CPU to recover without a hard reset, security continues to be enforced, but the operating system cannot properly respond to the failure because it was not possible to detect the failure.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] This is because kernel execution either halted or the program counter resumed execution from somewhere in an endless, and—usually—non-functional loop.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] This would be akin to either experiencing amnesia (kernel execution failure) or being trapped in a closed maze that always returns to the starting point (closed loops).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] If execution picks up after the crash by loading and running trojan code, the author of the trojan code can usurp control of all processes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle of least privilege forces code to run with the lowest privilege/permission level possible.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] This means that the code that resumes the code execution-whether trojan or simply code execution picking up from an unexpected location—would not have the ability to perform malicious or undesirable processes.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] One method used to accomplish this can be implemented in the microprocessor hardware.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, in the Intel x86 architecture the manufacturer designed four (ring 0 through ring 3) running "modes" with graduated degrees of access-much like security clearance systems in defence and intelligence agencies.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] As implemented in some operating systems, processes execute with a *potential privilege set* and an *active privilege set*.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] Such privilege sets are inherited from the parent as determined by the semantics of *fork()*.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] An executable file that performs a privileged function—thereby technically constituting a component of the TCB, and concomitantly termed a trusted program or trusted process—may also be marked with a set of privileges.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] This is a logical extension of the notions of set user ID and set group ID.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] The inheritance of file privileges by a process are determined by the semantics of the *exec()* family of system calls.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] The precise manner in which potential process privileges, actual process privileges, and file privileges interact can become complex.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, least privilege is practiced by forcing a process to run with only those privileges required by the task.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] Adherence to this model is quite complex as well as error-prone.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/principle-of-least-privilege] Least privilege has also been interpreted in the context of distribution of discretionary access control (DAC) permissions, for example asserting that giving user U read/write access to file F violates least privilege if U can complete their authorized tasks with only read permission.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] In computing, **privilege** is defined as the delegation of authority to perform security-relevant functions on a computer system.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] A privilege allows a user to perform an action with security consequences.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Examples of various privileges include the ability to create a new user, install software, or change kernel functions.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Users who have been delegated extra levels of control are called privileged.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Users who lack most privileges are defined as unprivileged, regular, or normal users.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Privileges can either be automatic, granted, or applied for.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] An automatic privilege exists when there is no requirement to have permission to perform an action.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] For example, on systems where people are required to log into a system to use it, logging out will not require a privilege.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Systems that do not implement file protection - such as MS-DOS - essentially give unlimited privilege to perform any action on a file.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] A granted privilege exists as a result of presenting some credential to the privilege granting authority.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] This is usually accomplished by logging on to a system with a username and password, and if the username and password supplied are correct, the user is granted additional privileges.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] A privilege is applied for by either an executed program issuing a request for advanced privileges, or by running some program to apply for the additional privileges.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] An example of a user applying for additional privileges is provided by the `sudo` command to run a command as superuser (*root*) user, or by the Kerberos authentication system.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Modern processor architectures have multiple CPU modes that allows the OS to run at different privilege levels.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Some processors have two levels (such as *user* and *supervisor*); i386+ processors have four levels (#0 with the most, #3 with the least privileges).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Tasks are tagged with a privilege level.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Resources (segments, pages, ports, etc.) and the privileged instructions are tagged with a demanded privilege level.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] When a task tries to use a resource, or execute a privileged instruction, the processor determines whether it has the permission (if not, a "protection fault" interrupt is generated).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] This prevents user tasks from damaging the OS or each other.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] In computer programming, exceptions related to privileged instruction violations may be caused when an array has been accessed out of bounds or an invalid pointer has been dereferenced when the invalid memory location referenced is a privileged location, such as one controlling device input/output.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] This is particularly more likely to occur in programming languages such as C, which use pointer arithmetic or do not check array bounds automatically.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Mark Miller has critiqued the framing of privilege as being poorly defined and hard to measure, and suggested that authority can be defined as the set of things a program can do, which is more helpful.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] On Unix-like systems, the superuser (commonly known as 'root') owns all the privileges.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Ordinary users are granted only enough permissions to accomplish their most common tasks.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] UNIX systems have built-in security features.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Most users cannot set up a new user account nor do other administrative procedures.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] The user “root” is a special user, something called super-user, which can do anything at all on the system.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] This high degree power is necessary to fully administer a UNIX system, but it also allows its user to make a mistake and cause system problems.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] On Windows NT-based systems, privileges are delegated in varying degrees.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] These delegations can be defined using the local security policy manager (`secpol.msc`).
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Windows defines a number of administrative privileges that can be assigned individually to users and/or groups.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] An account (user) holds only the privileges granted to it, either directly or indirectly through group memberships.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Upon installation a number of groups and accounts are created and privileges are granted to them.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] However, these grants can be changed at a later time or though a group policy.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Unlike Linux, no privileges are implicitly or permanently granted to a specific account.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Some administrative privileges (e.g. taking ownership of or restoring arbitrary files) are so powerful that if used with malicious intent they could allow the entire system to be compromised.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] With user account control (on by default since Windows Vista) Windows will strip the user token of these privileges at login.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Thus, if a user logs in with an account with broad system privileges, he/she will still not be *running* with these system privileges.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Whenever the user wants to perform administrative actions requiring any of the system privileges he/she will have to do this from an *elevated* process.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] When launching an *elevated* process, the user is made aware that his/her administrative privileges are being asserted through a prompt requiring his/her consent.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Not holding privileges until actually required is in keeping with the principle of least privilege.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Elevated processes will run with the full privileges of the *user*, not the full privileges of the *system*.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Even so, the privileges of the user may still be more than what is required for that particular process, thus not completely least privilege.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] The DOS-based Windows ME, Windows 98, Windows 95 and previous versions of non-NT Windows only operated on the FAT filesystem, did not support filesystem permissions and therefore privileges are effectively defeated on Windows NT-based systems that do not use the NTFS file system.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] The names used in the Windows source code end in either "privilege" or "logonright".
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] This has led to some confusion about what the full set of all these "rights" and "privileges" should be called.
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] Microsoft currently uses the term "user rights".
[src:cloud-entitlements-ciem/privilege-computing] In the past some other terms have also been used by Microsoft, such as "privilege rights" , "logon user rights" and "nt-rights".
